The Project Template and the Self-provisioner Role
Objectives
Configure default quotas, limit ranges, role bindings, and other restrictions for new projects, and manage permissions for users to self-provision new projects.
1️⃣ Project Creation in OpenShift
Kubernetes Concept
In Kubernetes, workloads are isolated using Namespaces.
Example:
namespace: dev
namespace: prod
But namespaces have two problems:
Problem 1 — Security Risk
Namespace metadata (labels/annotations) can affect security.
Example:
A policy controller might check namespace labels.
If users modify namespace labels →
they could bypass security policies.
________________________________________
Problem 2 — Listing Namespaces
In Kubernetes RBAC:
You cannot allow a user to list only some namespaces.
If you give permission:
list namespaces
User can see all namespaces in the cluster.
But organizations usually want:
User sees only their namespaces
________________________________________
2️⃣ OpenShift Solution: Projects
OpenShift introduces Projects.
👉 Project = Namespace + access control improvements
OpenShift API server does this:
1.	Gets all namespaces
2.	Filters namespaces user can access
3.	Returns them as Projects
So users only see their allowed projects.
________________________________________
3️⃣ ProjectRequest Resource
OpenShift adds another resource:
ProjectRequest
This enables self-service project creation.
Example command:
oc new-project dev-project
What happens internally:
1️⃣ User creates ProjectRequest
2️⃣ API server uses a project template
3️⃣ Namespace is created
4️⃣ Default permissions and policies are applied
So the namespace is not empty.
Admins can control what is created automatically.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Project Template
A Project Template defines what resources are automatically created when a new project is created.
Admins can add things like:
•	Roles
•	RoleBindings
•	ResourceQuotas
•	LimitRanges
•	NetworkPolicies
Purpose:
✔ Enforce organization policies
✔ Avoid manual setup for every project
✔ Provide secure default configuration
________________________________________
5️⃣ Example Resources in Project Template
1️⃣ RoleBindings
Give permissions automatically.
Default template gives:
admin role
to the user who created the project.
Example:
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: admin
  namespace: ${PROJECT_NAME}
roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: admin
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: ${PROJECT_ADMIN_USER}
Meaning:
User who requested the project becomes admin of that project.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Resource Quotas
Limits resources in a project.
Example:
kind: ResourceQuota
spec:
  hard:
    pods: "10"
    requests.cpu: "2"
    requests.memory: 4Gi
Meaning:
Project cannot use more than:
•	10 pods
•	2 CPU
•	4GB memory
________________________________________
3️⃣ LimitRanges
Provide default resource values for containers.
Example:
kind: LimitRange
spec:
  limits:
  - type: Container
    defaultRequest:
      cpu: 250m
      memory: 256Mi
    default:
      cpu: 500m
      memory: 512Mi
Purpose:
If developer forgets to define resources → OpenShift assigns defaults.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Network Policies
Control pod-to-pod traffic.
Example:
Allow only pods in same project to communicate.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Creating a Project Template
First generate the default template.
Command:
oc adm create-bootstrap-project-template -o yaml > template.yaml
This generates a YAML file.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Default Template Structure
Important sections:
apiVersion: template.openshift.io/v1
kind: Template
metadata:
  name: project-request
This defines a template object.
________________________________________
objects section
Defines resources created in the new project.
Example:
objects:
- kind: Project
- kind: RoleBinding
These resources are automatically created.
________________________________________
parameters section
Defines variables used in template.
Example:
parameters:
- name: PROJECT_NAME
- name: PROJECT_DISPLAYNAME
- name: PROJECT_DESCRIPTION
- name: PROJECT_ADMIN_USER
- name: PROJECT_REQUESTING_USER
When a user creates a project:
oc new-project dev
OpenShift replaces:
${PROJECT_NAME}
with
dev
________________________________________
8️⃣ Steps to Build Custom Project Template
Recommended process:
Step 1
Create a test namespace.
oc new-project test-project
________________________________________
Step 2
Create required resources.
Example:
oc create quota
oc create limitrange
oc create networkpolicy
Test them.
________________________________________
Step 3
Export resources in YAML.
Command:
oc get limitrange,resourcequota -o yaml
________________________________________
Step 4
Edit YAML
Remove fields like:
status
creationTimestamp
resourceVersion
Replace namespace with:
${PROJECT_NAME}
________________________________________
Step 5
Add them to template.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Apply the Template
Create the template in OpenShift.
Command:
oc create -f template.yaml -n openshift-config
________________________________________
🔟 Configure OpenShift to Use Template
Edit project configuration.
Command:
oc edit project.config.openshift.io/cluster
Add:
spec:
  projectRequestTemplate:
    name: project-request
Meaning:
Every time a user creates a project → this template is used.
________________________________________
1️⃣1️⃣ API Server Restart
After configuration:
OpenShift rolls out a new API server deployment.
Location:
openshift-apiserver namespace
Once rollout finishes:
New projects use the template.
________________________________________
1️⃣2️⃣ Reverting to Default Template
Remove the configuration.
Edit:
oc edit project.config.openshift.io/cluster
Change:
spec: {}
Now default behavior returns.
________________________________________
1️⃣3️⃣ Self-Provisioner Role
Self-provisioner role allows users to create projects themselves.
Default behavior:
All logged-in users can create projects.
Binding:
system:authenticated:oauth
Meaning:
Any authenticated user can run:
oc new-project myproject
________________________________________
1️⃣4️⃣ Check Self-Provisioner Role
Command:
oc describe clusterrolebinding self-provisioners
Example output:
Role: self-provisioner
Subjects:
Group system:authenticated:oauth
Meaning:
All authenticated users have this role.
________________________________________
1️⃣5️⃣ Important Annotation
rbac.authorization.kubernetes.io/autoupdate: true
Purpose:
If API server restarts → default roles are restored automatically.
To modify role binding → disable this.
________________________________________
1️⃣6️⃣ Disable Self-Provisioning
Step 1:
Disable auto updates.
oc annotate clusterrolebinding/self-provisioners \
rbac.authorization.kubernetes.io/autoupdate=false
________________________________________
Step 2:
Remove users.
oc patch clusterrolebinding.rbac self-provisioners \
-p '{"subjects": null}'
Now users cannot create projects.
________________________________________
1️⃣7️⃣ Allow Only Specific Group
Instead of everyone:
Allow only a group.
Edit:
oc edit clusterrolebinding self-provisioners
Example:
subjects:
- kind: Group
  name: provisioners
Now only this group can create projects.
________________________________________
1️⃣8️⃣ Important Warning
Even if self-provisioning is disabled:
Users with namespace permissions can still run:
oc create namespace
That namespace does not use project template.
________________________________________
1️⃣9️⃣ Quick Architecture Flow
User runs
oc new-project dev
↓
Creates
ProjectRequest
↓
OpenShift API server
↓
Applies
Project Template
↓
Creates
Namespace
RoleBindings
ResourceQuotas
LimitRanges
NetworkPolicies
________________________________________
2️⃣0️⃣ One-Line Exam Definition
A Project Template in OpenShift defines the default resources such as role bindings, quotas, limit ranges, and policies that are automatically created when a new project is requested.


